  "response": "RAM (Random Access Memory) can go bad due to several reasons:\n\n1. Physical damage\n- Exposure to extreme temperatures\n- Static electricity\n- Physical impact or rough handling\n- Moisture or liquid exposure\n\n2. Manufacturing defects\n- Poor quality control\n- Internal microscopic flaws\n- Weak manufacturing processes\n\n3. Age and wear\n- Continuous use over time\n- Frequent power cycles\n- Degradation of electronic components\n\n4. Electrical issues\n- Power surges\n- Unstable power supply\n- Overheating of computer components\n- Incorrect voltage or improper power management\n\n5. Overclocking\n- Pushing RAM beyond recommended performance limits\n- Increased heat generation\n- Excessive stress on memory modules\n\nSigns of failing RAM include:\n- Blue screen errors\n- System crashes\n- Random program freezes\n- Corrupted files\n- Unexplained computer performance issues\n\nDetection methods:\n- Memory diagnostic tools\n- Built-in Windows Memory Diagnostic\n- Third-party RAM testing software\n- Professional hardware diagnostic services\n\nPrevention involves:\n- Using quality RAM\n- Proper computer maintenance\n- Adequate cooling\n- Stable power supply\n- Avoiding physical mishandling",
